Problem:
--------
Design a stack that supports push, pop, top, and retrieving the minimum element in constant time.
Implement the MinStack class:
MinStack() initializes the stack object.
void push(int value) pushes the element value onto the stack.
void pop() removes the element on the top of the stack.
int top() gets the top element of the stack.
int getMin() retrieves the minimum element in the stack.
You must implement a solution with O(1) time complexity for each function.
 
Example 1:
Input:["MinStack","push","push","push","getMin","pop","top","getMin"]
[[],[-2],[0],[-3],[],[],[],[]]
Output:[null,null,null,null,-3,null,0,-2]

Solution:
--------
class MinStack {
    class Pair{
        int first;
        int second;
        Pair(int first,int second){
            this.first = first;
            this.second = second;
        }
    }
    Stack<Pair> st;
    public MinStack() {
        st = new Stack<>();
    }   
    public void push(int val) {
       if(st.isEmpty()){
           st.push(new Pair(val,val));
       } 
       else{
          int minVal = Math.min(val,st.peek().second);
          st.push(new Pair(val,minVal));
       }  
    }    
    public void pop() {
        st.pop();
    }    
    public int top() {
        return st.peek().first;
    }
    
    public int getMin() {
        return st.peek().second;
    }
}

Time Complexity:O(1) for all operations (push, pop, top, getMin) as they involve constant time operations on the stack.
Space Complexity:O(n) where n is the number of elements in the stack, as we store pairs of values (element and minimum) in the stack.
